ce:section.ce:para:
The photo-induced charge pairs separated efficiency during the reaction process is investigated through the PL spectroscopy in Fig. 6
                     a. The three samples demonstrated the similar emission peaks at 420 nm because of the recombination process of intrinsic excitation electron carriers [18,66]. Significantly, the CeO2-CH/CDs have a lower PL intensity comparing to the other two catalysts. Photo-induced charge-hole pair separation efficiency has been significantly improved for the CDs doped sample. The CeO2-CH/CDs catalyst also has the highest charge carrier density (Fig. 6b). The curves are composed of two semicircles, a small one over the high frequency area is the contact resistance (Rc
                     ) and a bigger one over the middle frequency is the charge-transfer resistance (Rct
                     ). The CeO2-CH/CDs catalyst has the lowest charge transfer resistance (Rct
                     ) in Fig. 6c. N2-TPD analyses are also applied to depict N2 adsorption abilities. In Fig. 6b, the peak at around 200 °C is corresponding to nitrogen physical adsorption process. There is almost no N2 adsorption for original CeO2-CZH. Two peaks at 350 °C and 460 °C are most likely attributed to chemical adsorption active sites for the separated phases of CeO2 and CH in CeO2-CH, respectively. Three chemical adsorption active regions, CeO2, CH and CDs, are exhibited in the CeO2-CH/CDs sample. As far as we know, the chemisorption plays a primary role in the N2 photo-fixation process [67,68]. The CDs doped CeO2/CH heterojunction has more absorption active sites than other two catalysts to further obtain the higher N2 adsorption capacities, and this is one of the contributing factors for the promoted N2 photo-fixation rate.
